2. Azure Database Fundamentals
âœ… PaaS vs IaaS vs SaaS
These are cloud service models, each offering different levels of control, flexibility, and management:
Model	Full Form	What It Means	Azure Example
IaaS	Infrastructure as a Service	You manage the OS, DB, and apps. Azure provides VMs, networking, and storage.	Azure Virtual Machines (SQL on VM)
PaaS	Platform as a Service	Azure manages OS, DB engine, patches, and backups. You focus on databases and apps.	Azure SQL Database, Azure SQL Managed Instance
SaaS	Software as a Service	Everything (infrastructure + software) is managed. You just use the app.	Microsoft 365, Power BI
Summary:
â€¢	IaaS = full control, more maintenance.
â€¢	PaaS = less admin, more agility.
â€¢	SaaS = no admin, just use it.
________________________________________
âœ… Azure SQL Database Tiers
Azure SQL Database (PaaS) offers service tiers for different workloads, with varying performance, pricing, and features.
Main tiers:
1.	Basic / General Purpose â€“ For light workloads, dev/test. Cheaper.
2.	Standard / Business Critical â€“ Higher availability, IOPS, and speed.
3.	Premium â€“ Low-latency and high-performance databases.
4.	Hyperscale â€“ For massive databases (up to 100 TB), instant scaling.
You choose tiers based on:
â€¢	Performance needs (e.g., high transactions)
â€¢	Redundancy & failover
â€¢	Cost vs features
________________________________________
âœ… DTU vs vCore Models
These are pricing and performance models in Azure SQL Database.
1. DTU (Database Transaction Unit) model:
â€¢	Pre-configured bundles of CPU, memory, and I/O.
â€¢	Simple to use but less flexible.
â€¢	Best for small apps or when you donâ€™t want to fine-tune resources.
ðŸ’¡ Example: 50 DTUs = enough power for a small app with light workloads.
2. vCore (Virtual Core) model:
â€¢	You choose CPU (vCores), RAM, and storage separately.
â€¢	More transparent and cost-effective for large/production workloads.
â€¢	Allows Azure Hybrid Benefit (if you already have SQL Server licenses).
ðŸ’¡ Example: 4 vCores, 16 GB RAM, 250 GB storage = medium workload flexibility.
ðŸ“Œ DTU is easier, vCore is more customizable.
________________________________________
âœ… SQL Managed Instance vs Azure SQL VM
Both are ways to run SQL Server in Azure, but they differ in how much you manage:
Feature	Azure SQL Managed Instance	Azure SQL VM
Service Model	PaaS	IaaS
Management	Microsoft manages OS, updates, backups	You manage everything (like on-prem)
Features	Near full SQL Server compatibility (agent, cross-db queries)	100% SQL Server control
Use Case	Lift-and-shift with minimal admin	Full SQL Server control, custom settings
Pricing	Higher due to automation and PaaS benefits	Can be cheaper with licensing (Hybrid Benefit)
ðŸ”¹ Use Managed Instance if you want low admin overhead with advanced SQL features.
ðŸ”¹ Use SQL on VM if you need legacy setup, full control, or unsupported features in PaaS.
________________________________________
Summary
Concept	Key Point
PaaS vs IaaS vs SaaS	Levels of management responsibility (PaaS is ideal for DBAs)
SQL Database Tiers	Choose tier based on performance and size requirements
DTU vs vCore	DTU = simple bundles; vCore = customizable, transparent billing
Managed Instance vs SQL VM	Managed Instance = modern PaaS with SQL features; VM = legacy/full control
3. Deploy and Configure Azure SQL Resources
âœ… Creating SQL Database via Portal, CLI, PowerShell
There are 3 main ways to create an Azure SQL Database, depending on your preference or automation need:
1. Azure Portal (GUI)
â€¢	Easiest method, browser-based.
â€¢	Walkthrough wizard lets you choose server, performance tier, backup options.
â€¢	Good for beginners or small setups.
ðŸ’¡ Example: Go to "Create Resource" â†’ "SQL Database" â†’ fill form â†’ click Create.
2. Azure CLI (Command-line)
â€¢	Scriptable and great for automation.
â€¢	Cross-platform (az sql db create)
â€¢	Ideal for DevOps and scripting in CI/CD.
ðŸ’¡ Example command:
bash
CopyEdit
az sql db create --name mydb --server myserver --resource-group mygroup --service-objective S0
3. PowerShell
â€¢	Preferred in Windows environments or existing PowerShell automation.
â€¢	Full control over Azure resource provisioning.
ðŸ’¡ Example:
powershell
CopyEdit
New-AzSqlDatabase -ResourceGroupName "mygroup" -ServerName "myserver" -DatabaseName "mydb" -RequestedServiceObjectiveName "S0"
________________________________________
âœ… Geo-replication and Failover Groups
These features provide business continuity and disaster recovery for Azure SQL Databases:
1. Geo-replication:
â€¢	Creates a read-only secondary DB in another region.
â€¢	Manual failover.
â€¢	Use case: reporting, read-scale, or disaster recovery.
ðŸ’¡ Enabled on Premium / Business Critical / Hyperscale tiers.
2. Failover Groups:
â€¢	Provides automatic failover between primary and secondary databases across regions.
â€¢	Supports read-write and read-only listener endpoints.
â€¢	Use case: high availability + automatic region failover.
ðŸ’¡ Ideal for multi-region apps with low downtime tolerance.
________________________________________
âœ… Elastic Pools vs Single Databases
These are cost management models for Azure SQL databases:
1. Single Database:
â€¢	Isolated resources (CPU, memory).
â€¢	You pay per database.
â€¢	Best for steady, predictable workloads.
ðŸ’¡ Ideal if each DB has consistent usage.
2. Elastic Pool:
â€¢	Shared resources among multiple DBs.
â€¢	You pay for the pool, not each database.
â€¢	Ideal for variable, bursty workloads.
ðŸ’¡ Example: 20 small databases, each active at different times.
ðŸ“Œ Summary:
â€¢	Use Single DB for consistent workloads.
â€¢	Use Elastic Pools for cost efficiency with multiple fluctuating workloads.
________________________________________
âœ… Deployment Automation (ARM Templates, Bicep)
These tools automate resource provisioning using Infrastructure as Code (IaC):
1. ARM Templates:
â€¢	JSON-based templates.
â€¢	Define full infrastructure: SQL DB, server, network, etc.
â€¢	Used in CI/CD pipelines and repeatable deployments.
ðŸ’¡ Example structure:
json
CopyEdit
{
  "type": "Microsoft.Sql/servers/databases",
  "name": "[parameters('databaseName')]",
  "properties": {
    "collation": "SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS",
    "maxSizeBytes": "1073741824",
    "requestedServiceObjectiveName": "S0"
  }
}
2. Bicep (Newer and easier):
â€¢	A simplified syntax for ARM.
â€¢	Compiles into ARM under the hood.
â€¢	Easier to read and write.
ðŸ’¡ Bicep vs ARM: Think of Bicep as TypeScript, ARM as JavaScript.
ðŸ“Œ Both are used to automate SQL DB creation, backups, failover groups, etc., across environments (dev, staging, prod).
________________________________________
Summary Table
Topic	Summary
Creating SQL DB	Use Portal for ease, CLI/PowerShell for automation
Geo-replication & Failover Groups	For regional redundancy; failover groups = auto switch
Elastic Pools vs Single DBs	Elastic = cost-efficient for many DBs with varying loads
Deployment Automation	Use ARM or Bicep for reliable, repeatable, version-controlled deployments
4. Configure High Availability and Disaster Recovery
âœ… HA/DR Design Strategies
HA/DR (High Availability and Disaster Recovery) strategies ensure business continuity and data protection.
Design goals:
â€¢	HA = Keep the service online during hardware or software failures (minimal downtime).
â€¢	DR = Recover after catastrophic failures (e.g., region-wide outages).
Azure SQL Database built-in options:
â€¢	Zone-redundant deployments (Business Critical tier or Hyperscale)
â€¢	Auto-failover groups (DR across regions)
â€¢	Geo-replication (manual failover)
â€¢	Point-in-time restore (PITR)
â€¢	Long-term retention (LTR) for backups
ðŸ“Œ Choose HA/DR tools based on RPO (Recovery Point Objective) and RTO (Recovery Time Objective) needs.
________________________________________
âœ… Availability Zones and Sets
Availability Zones:
â€¢	Physically separate datacenters within the same Azure region.
â€¢	Used in Business Critical tier and Hyperscale to keep replicas in different zones.
â€¢	Automatic failover between zones if one goes down.
ðŸ’¡ Enabled by choosing Zone-Redundant configuration during deployment.
Availability Sets (for VMs):
â€¢	Ensures VM instances are distributed across multiple fault and update domains.
â€¢	Applies only to IaaS-based SQL Servers (SQL on VM).
ðŸ“Œ Use Zones for PaaS (Azure SQL DB/MI) and Sets for IaaS (SQL on VM).
________________________________________
âœ… Failover Groups and Auto-Failover
Failover Groups provide geo-redundancy and automatic failover for Azure SQL Database and SQL Managed Instances.
Features:
â€¢	Automatic replication to paired region (read-write and read-only replicas).
â€¢	Use listener endpoints for seamless failover access (<servername>.database.windows.net).
â€¢	Supports manual or automatic failover based on health checks.
ðŸ’¡ Best for mission-critical apps needing near-zero downtime across regions.
ðŸ“Œ Works only with vCore model, not DTU.
________________________________________
âœ… Geo-Replication Step-by-Step
Active Geo-Replication = Manual, readable secondary DB in another region (PaaS SQL DB only).
ðŸ”§ Step-by-step:
1.	Go to your Azure SQL database in the Portal.
2.	Click on Geo-Replication under "Settings."
3.	Select a target region.
4.	Choose or create a target server in that region.
5.	Confirm and start replication.
ðŸ’¡ Secondary is read-only and used for reporting or DR.
ðŸ’¡ You can failover manually from portal, PowerShell, or CLI.
ðŸ“Œ Use Geo-replication when you need read-scale and manual DR.
________________________________________
âœ… PITR, LTR, and Backup Policies
These are data recovery features for Azure SQL Database:
1. PITR (Point-In-Time Restore):
â€¢	Restore your DB to any point in the last 7â€“35 days (default = 7 days).
â€¢	Uses automated backups.
â€¢	Fast recovery from accidental deletes or corruption.
2. LTR (Long-Term Retention):
â€¢	Store full backups for up to 10 years.
â€¢	Useful for audit, compliance, or archival.
ðŸ’¡ Configure on each database (e.g., weekly/monthly retention policies).
3. Backup Policies:
â€¢	Azure takes automatic backups of your SQL DB.
â€¢	Includes full, differential, and transaction log backups.
â€¢	Backup frequency depends on tier:
o	Every 5-10 minutes for transaction logs
o	Weekly full, daily differential
ðŸ“Œ Backups are stored in RA-GRS storage (geo-redundant).
________________________________________
ðŸ”„ Summary Table
Feature	Purpose	Use Case
HA/DR Design	Ensure uptime + recovery	Always-on service and data protection
Availability Zones/Sets	Physical isolation within a region	Intra-region failover
Failover Groups	Geo-redundant auto failover	Critical apps needing RTO ~ seconds
Geo-Replication	Manual DR + read replicas	Reporting, low-cost DR
PITR	Restore recent data (7â€“35 days)	Accidental deletions
LTR	Store backups for years	Legal/audit/compliance
Backup Policies	Auto backups + restore support	Built-in reliability
5. Monitor and Optimize Operational Resources
âœ… Azure Monitor and Log Analytics
Azure Monitor:
â€¢	Centralized platform for monitoring the health, performance, and availability of your Azure resources.
â€¢	Collects metrics, logs, and diagnostics from Azure SQL Database.
â€¢	Alerts you on issues like high DTU usage, slow queries, or failed connections.
Log Analytics (part of Azure Monitor):
â€¢	Uses Kusto Query Language (KQL) to query and analyze collected logs.
â€¢	Helps you troubleshoot, audit, and visualize SQL performance and usage patterns.
ðŸ’¡ You can connect Azure SQL Diagnostics to Log Analytics for deep insights.
________________________________________
âœ… Query Performance Insight
A built-in feature of Azure SQL that helps you analyze top-consuming queries in terms of:
â€¢	CPU time
â€¢	Execution count
â€¢	Duration
Key benefits:
â€¢	Identify expensive or poorly written queries.
â€¢	Track performance trends over time.
â€¢	Drill into query text, execution plan, and wait time breakdown.
ðŸ’¡ Great for spotting performance regressions after code or schema changes.
ðŸ“Œ Available directly in the Azure Portal under your SQL DB â†’ Intelligent Performance â†’ Query Performance Insight.
________________________________________
âœ… Wait Stats, Missing Indexes, CPU/Disk Bottlenecks
These are critical indicators of SQL performance issues:
Wait Stats:
â€¢	Show why SQL queries are delayed (e.g., waiting for memory, CPU, locks).
â€¢	Helps diagnose resource contention.
ðŸ’¡ Example waits: PAGEIOLATCH (I/O wait), SOS_SCHEDULER_YIELD (CPU pressure)
Missing Indexes:
â€¢	SQL Engine suggests missing indexes that could improve query speed.
â€¢	Can be found via DMVs (sys.dm_db_missing_index_details).
ðŸ’¡ Act only after analyzing workload impactâ€”too many indexes can slow writes.
CPU/Disk Bottlenecks:
â€¢	High CPU = inefficient queries or underpowered tier.
â€¢	High Disk I/O = missing indexes, too much tempdb usage, or large reads.
ðŸ“Œ Monitor these via:
â€¢	Azure Monitor Metrics
â€¢	Query Store
â€¢	Dynamic Management Views (DMVs)
________________________________________
âœ… Extended Events in Azure SQL
Extended Events (XEvents) are a lightweight monitoring system to capture and analyze:
â€¢	Long-running queries
â€¢	Deadlocks
â€¢	Errors and warnings
â€¢	Wait types, execution plans, and much more
In Azure SQL:
â€¢	You can create and manage XEvents using:
o	T-SQL (CREATE EVENT SESSION)
o	Azure Portal (for SQL Managed Instance only)
ðŸ’¡ Events are stored in ring buffers or file targets for later analysis.
ðŸ“Œ Best for custom performance troubleshooting without significant overhead.
________________________________________
ðŸ”„ Summary Table
Tool / Concept	Purpose	Use Case
Azure Monitor	Collects metrics/logs	Track health and usage
Log Analytics	Analyze logs with KQL	Deep diagnostics & alerts
Query Performance Insight	View top resource-consuming queries	Tune slow or high-impact queries
Wait Stats	Reveal query delays	Pinpoint CPU, I/O, locking issues
Missing Indexes	Suggest performance improvements	Speed up slow queries
CPU/Disk Monitoring	Detect bottlenecks	Optimize performance tier or code
Extended Events	Capture detailed runtime data	Advanced troubleshooting & tracing
6. Optimize Query Performance
âœ… Execution Plans: Estimated vs Actual
Execution Plan:
â€¢	A blueprint the SQL Engine uses to retrieve query results.
â€¢	Helps DBAs and developers understand query performance.
ðŸŸ¨ Estimated Execution Plan:
â€¢	Generated before the query runs.
â€¢	Shows SQL Serverâ€™s prediction of how it will execute the query.
â€¢	No runtime dataâ€”uses statistics and cost estimates only.
ðŸ’¡ Use when you want to preview performance without running a heavy query.
ðŸŸ© Actual Execution Plan:
â€¢	Includes runtime data: row counts, I/O, CPU usage, actual operations.
â€¢	Helps you verify if the plan matched reality.
ðŸ“Œ Use actual plans for debugging slow queries or analyzing regressions.
________________________________________
âœ… Statistics and Cardinality
Statistics:
â€¢	Data about distribution of values in a column (e.g., how many rows per value).
â€¢	SQL Server uses them to estimate row counts, choose join types, and indexes.
ðŸ’¡ Outdated statistics = bad estimates = bad plans.
â€¢	Automatically updated by default, but manual updates may be needed for:
o	Large data changes
o	Poor performance
Cardinality:
â€¢	Estimated number of rows returned by each operation in a query.
â€¢	Based on statistics.
ðŸ“Œ Large gaps between estimated vs actual cardinality = potential statistics issue or suboptimal plan.
________________________________________
âœ… Index Tuning: Clustered, Non-Clustered, Covering
1. Clustered Index:
â€¢	Physically sorts table rows by key column.
â€¢	Only one per table.
â€¢	Default index on primary key (unless specified otherwise).
ðŸ’¡ Fast for range scans (e.g., BETWEEN, ORDER BY).
2. Non-Clustered Index:
â€¢	Separate from table data.
â€¢	Points to the actual row using a row locator (RID or clustered key).
â€¢	Can have multiple per table.
ðŸ’¡ Ideal for filter conditions, frequent searches.
3. Covering Index:
â€¢	A non-clustered index that includes all columns needed by the query.
â€¢	Prevents need to look up the base table (no bookmark lookup).
ðŸ’¡ Boosts performance by reducing I/O.
ðŸ“Œ Use Index DMVs (sys.dm_db_index_usage_stats) + Query Store to tune usage.
________________________________________
âœ… Query Store and Plan Regression
Query Store:
â€¢	Built-in feature to track query performance over time.
â€¢	Stores:
o	Query texts
o	Execution plans
o	Performance metrics (CPU, duration, reads)
Plan Regression:
â€¢	Happens when SQL Server suddenly uses a worse plan for a previously fast query.
o	Caused by plan cache eviction, parameter sniffing, or stats changes.
ðŸ’¡ Query Store helps detect and force a good plan:
sql
CopyEdit
EXEC sp_query_store_force_plan @query_id = 1, @plan_id = 2;
ðŸ“Œ Use it for performance history, troubleshooting, and plan stabilization.
________________________________________
âœ… PBQ-Style Performance Tuning Examples
PBQ = Problem â†’ Bottleneck â†’ Query Fix
This approach helps structure performance troubleshooting:
________________________________________
ðŸ”¸ Example 1
Problem: Query is slow with high CPU
Bottleneck: High estimated vs actual row count
Query Fix:
â€¢	Update statistics
â€¢	Rewrite query to improve cardinality
â€¢	Consider using OPTIMIZE FOR hint
________________________________________
ðŸ”¸ Example 2
Problem: Scan on a large table
Bottleneck: Missing index
Query Fix:
â€¢	Create a non-clustered covering index
sql
CopyEdit
CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX IX_Customers_Email
ON Customers(Email)
INCLUDE (FirstName, LastName);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¸ Example 3
Problem: Query slow after deployment
Bottleneck: Plan regression
Query Fix:
â€¢	Use Query Store to revert to previous plan
â€¢	Check parameter sniffing
________________________________________
ðŸ§  Summary Table
Concept	Purpose	Key Benefit
Estimated Plan	Shows intended plan	Preview, debugging
Actual Plan	Includes runtime stats	Pinpoint real issues
Statistics & Cardinality	Improve estimate accuracy	Better plan selection
Indexes	Speed up queries	Lower I/O & CPU
Query Store	Track plans & fix regressions	Long-term visibility
PBQ Framework	Structured tuning method	Focused diagnostics
7. Implement Security
âœ… Network Isolation (Firewall, VNet Rules)
Controlling who can connect to your Azure SQL Database is the first layer of defense.
1. Firewall Rules
â€¢	Control access by IP address.
â€¢	Set server-level (applies to all DBs) or database-level rules.
â€¢	Can allow or block public internet access.
ðŸ’¡ Example: Allow IP range 203.0.113.0/24 to access the DB.
2. Virtual Network (VNet) Rules
â€¢	Restrict access to specific Azure Virtual Networks.
â€¢	Use Private Endpoints to eliminate public exposure.
â€¢	Stronger isolation for internal-only or secure apps.
ðŸ“Œ Combine firewall + VNet for layered security.
________________________________________
âœ… Authentication (SQL, AAD, Managed Identities)
Controlling who you are when accessing the database.
1. SQL Authentication
â€¢	Username/password-based.
â€¢	Traditional method.
â€¢	Must be stored and rotated securely.
2. Azure Active Directory (AAD) Authentication
â€¢	Use Azure AD users/groups to access the DB.
â€¢	Supports MFA, SSO, and centralized identity management.
â€¢	Preferred for enterprise security.
ðŸ’¡ Example:
sql
CopyEdit
CREATE USER [aad_user@domain.com] FROM EXTERNAL PROVIDER;
3. Managed Identities
â€¢	Use the identity of the Azure service (like an Azure Function or VM).
â€¢	No credentials storedâ€”automated, secure access.
â€¢	Great for app-to-DB access (no hardcoded secrets).
ðŸ“Œ Recommended for internal app authentication to Azure SQL.
________________________________________
âœ… RBAC and Least Privilege Model
Control what authenticated users can do in Azure.
1. RBAC (Role-Based Access Control):
â€¢	Assign roles like Contributor, Reader, or SQL DB Contributor at Azure level (resource group, DB).
â€¢	Controls who can manage resources, not query data.
2. SQL Roles (Inside the DB):
â€¢	Control data-level permissions.
â€¢	Roles: db_datareader, db_owner, db_ddladmin, etc.
Least Privilege Model:
â€¢	Give users only the minimum access they need.
â€¢	Avoid giving db_owner unless absolutely necessary.
â€¢	Apply principle of least privilege consistently.
ðŸ“Œ Helps reduce risk of accidental damage or misuse.
________________________________________
âœ… TDE, Always Encrypted, Data Masking
These features protect data at rest and in use:
1. TDE (Transparent Data Encryption)
â€¢	Encrypts database, backups, and transaction logs at rest.
â€¢	Enabled by default on Azure SQL.
â€¢	No application changes needed.
ðŸ’¡ Uses a built-in service-managed key (or customer-managed key if needed).
2. Always Encrypted
â€¢	Encrypts sensitive columns (e.g., SSN, credit card) client-side.
â€¢	Data is encrypted before reaching the server.
â€¢	Only the app (with keys) can decrypt.
ðŸ’¡ Ensures SQL Server never sees plaintext.
3. Dynamic Data Masking
â€¢	Obscures sensitive data (e.g., show XXXX-XXXX-1234 instead of full card number).
â€¢	For read-only protection, not encryption.
ðŸ’¡ Useful for dev/test environments or casual data access.
________________________________________
âœ… Auditing, Threat Detection, Defender for SQL
Tools to monitor and detect security issues in Azure SQL:
1. Auditing
â€¢	Logs who accessed what, when, and how.
â€¢	Stores logs in Log Analytics, Event Hub, or Storage Account.
â€¢	Helps with compliance (e.g., HIPAA, GDPR).
ðŸ’¡ Example: Log all SELECT, INSERT, DELETE activity.
2. Advanced Threat Protection (Deprecated term, now part of Defender for SQL)
â€¢	Detects suspicious activities:
o	SQL injection attempts
o	Unusual logins
o	Data exfiltration
ðŸ’¡ Sends email alerts and recommendations.
3. Microsoft Defender for SQL
â€¢	Unified security dashboard.
â€¢	Includes vulnerability assessment, threat detection, and security score.
â€¢	Scans for:
o	Missing patches
o	Misconfigured access
o	Insecure permissions
ðŸ“Œ Recommended for enterprise-grade SQL security monitoring.
________________________________________
ðŸ”’ Summary Table
Feature	Purpose	Key Benefit
Firewall / VNet Rules	Network access control	Isolate from public internet
SQL / AAD / Managed Identity	Authentication methods	Secure user/app login
RBAC + SQL Roles	Access control	Enforce least privilege
TDE	Encryption at rest	Automatic, default protection
Always Encrypted	Encryption in use	End-to-end protection
Data Masking	Obfuscate sensitive info	Visual-only protection
Auditing	Log access & actions	Compliance, accountability
Threat Detection & Defender	Alert on threats	Proactive security response
8. Automate Database Tasks
âœ… SQL Agent Jobs in Azure
In SQL Server (on-prem/VM):
â€¢	SQL Server Agent is used to schedule jobs, such as:
o	Backups
o	Index rebuilds
o	ETL workflows
o	Custom scripts (T-SQL, PowerShell)
In Azure SQL Database (PaaS):
â€¢	SQL Agent is not available, but you can achieve similar functionality using:
Alternative	Description
Elastic Jobs	PaaS-native job automation for Azure SQL DBs
Azure Automation + Runbooks	General-purpose automation (PowerShell, scripts)
Azure Logic Apps / Functions	For serverless job workflows
Azure Data Factory	For ETL/data movement tasks
ðŸ“Œ For SQL Managed Instance: SQL Agent is supported, just like on-prem SQL Server.
________________________________________
âœ… Azure Automation
A cloud-based automation platform to run scripts on schedule or on demand.
Features:
â€¢	Run PowerShell or Python scripts.
â€¢	Ideal for database maintenance tasks, such as:
o	Index rebuilds
o	User creation
o	Auditing checks
o	SQL backups for VMs
Benefits:
â€¢	No infrastructure to manage.
â€¢	Can authenticate using Managed Identity.
â€¢	Integrates with Azure Monitor, Log Analytics, Webhooks.
ðŸ“Œ Works great as a SQL Agent alternative for Azure SQL DB.
________________________________________
âœ… Runbooks and Webhooks
Runbooks:
â€¢	Script files (PowerShell or Python) inside Azure Automation.
â€¢	You can schedule them, run manually, or trigger by alert.
ðŸ’¡ Example:
â€¢	Runbook to shrink logs or rebuild indexes weekly.
Webhooks:
â€¢	Allow external apps to trigger a runbook via URL.
â€¢	Secure way to call scripts from external systems, alerts, or CI/CD pipelines.
ðŸ’¡ Example: A webhook that triggers a runbook when CPU hits 90%, or after a GitHub deployment.
ðŸ“Œ Enables event-driven automation across systems.
________________________________________
âœ… PowerShell for DB Admin
PowerShell is ideal for automating Azure SQL administration tasks, such as:
Common commands:
â€¢	Create database:
powershell
CopyEdit
