9. Perform Backup and Restore
âœ… Automated Backups in Azure
Azure SQL Database (PaaS) provides automatic, continuous backups with no manual setup required.
Key Features:
â€¢	Full backups: Every week
â€¢	Differential backups: Every 12â€“24 hours
â€¢	Transaction log backups: Every 5â€“10 minutes
ðŸ” Stored in RA-GRS (geo-redundant storage) by default.
ðŸ“Œ Backup retention:
â€¢	7 to 35 days (configurable) for Point-In-Time Restore (PITR)
â€¢	Can be extended for compliance using Long-Term Retention (LTR)
ðŸ“ Applies to:
â€¢	Azure SQL Database (single/elastic pool)
â€¢	Azure SQL Managed Instance
________________________________________
âœ… Point-In-Time Restore (PITR)
Allows you to restore the database to any moment within the retention window (default: last 7 days).
Use Cases:
â€¢	Accidental data deletion
â€¢	Bad deployments
â€¢	Corruption
How it works:
â€¢	Creates a new database from backup at a specific time.
â€¢	Done via Azure Portal, PowerShell, CLI, or REST API.
ðŸ’¡ Example via Azure CLI:
bash
CopyEdit
az sql db restore --dest-name newdb --name originaldb --server myserver --resource-group myrg --time "2025-07-25T15:30:00Z"
ðŸ“Œ PITR is fast, but restores to a new database, not over the existing one.
________________________________________
âœ… LTR (Long-Term Retention) for Compliance
Used for audits, legal, or business compliance where you need to store backups for months or years.
Key Features:
â€¢	Store weekly full backups for up to 10 years
â€¢	Can configure weekly, monthly, yearly policies
â€¢	Stored in separate backup vault (not standard PITR location)
ðŸ’¡ Example: "Retain 1 backup per month for 5 years"
Configuration:
â€¢	Azure Portal: Under "Manage Backups"
â€¢	Azure CLI:
bash
CopyEdit
az sql db ltr-policy set --name mydb --server myserver --resource-group myrg --weekly-retention P12W --monthly-retention P5Y
ðŸ“Œ Restore LTR backups even after the database is deleted.
________________________________________
âœ… Manual Backup via SSMS
Azure SQL PaaS databases (Azure SQL Database and MI) do not support native manual backups via SSMS like on-prem SQL Server.
Alternatives:
1.	Export to BACPAC file:
o	Use SSMS or Azure Portal
o	BACPAC = schema + data (for small/mid-size DBs)
o	Stored in Azure Blob Storage
ðŸ’¡ In SSMS: Right-click DB â†’ Tasks â†’ Export Data-tier Application
2.	For SQL Server on Azure VM:
o	Manual .bak file backups via SSMS are fully supported.
ðŸ“Œ Use BACPAC only for archival, migration, or dev/testâ€”not as a true backup/restore mechanism.
________________________________________
âœ… Restoring to New Region or Server
You can restore a database to:
â€¢	A different logical server in the same region
â€¢	A completely different Azure region (for DR/migration)
Options:
1.	Using PITR or LTR:
o	Select a different server or region as the target
o	Azure handles the cross-region restore (if using geo-redundant backups)
2.	Geo-restore (if original region is down):
o	Uses latest geo-replicated backup
o	Available in paired region even if original region is unavailable
ðŸ’¡ CLI Example:
bash
CopyEdit
az sql db restore --dest-name restoredDb --resource-group myrg --server newserver --geo-redundant
ðŸ“Œ Important: Restoring to a new region takes longer and may have higher RTO depending on backup location.
________________________________________
ðŸ”„ Summary Table
Feature	Purpose	Notes
Automated Backups	Built-in, no setup	Used for PITR & LTR
PITR	Restore to any point in recent past	Up to 35 days
LTR	Long-term backup retention for compliance	Up to 10 years
Manual Backup (SSMS)	Only via BACPAC (PaaS)	Full .bak supported only in Azure VMs
Restore to New Region/Server	Disaster recovery or migration	Uses geo-backups
10. Configure Authentication and Authorization
âœ… Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
RBAC is used in Azure to manage who can perform what actions on which resources.
Key Elements:
â€¢	Role assignments: Bind a user or group to a role on a scope (e.g., subscription, resource group, server).
â€¢	Built-in roles:
o	Reader: View-only access
o	Contributor: Modify but canâ€™t manage access
o	SQL Server Contributor: Manage SQL servers
o	SQL DB Contributor: Manage SQL databases
ðŸ“Œ RBAC controls resource-level access in Azureâ€”not actual data access inside the database.
ðŸ’¡ Use least privilege principle: give users only what they need.
________________________________________
âœ… Azure AD Groups and Users
Azure Active Directory (AAD) is Azureâ€™s identity service for centralized authentication.
Users:
â€¢	Individual Azure AD users can be granted access to Azure SQL.
â€¢	Login is passwordless or integrated (SSO, MFA).
Groups:
â€¢	Azure AD security groups allow assigning permissions to many users at once.
â€¢	Use groups to apply consistent and scalable access (recommended).
Azure SQL Integration:
â€¢	Use AAD authentication instead of SQL auth for better security.
â€¢	Create DB users from Azure AD:
sql
CopyEdit
CREATE USER [alice@contoso.com] FROM EXTERNAL PROVIDER;
ðŸ’¡ Roles (like db_datareader, db_owner) can be assigned to AAD users/groups.
ðŸ“Œ Benefits: MFA, SSO, central identity management, no stored credentials.
________________________________________
âœ… Login Auditing and Session Monitoring
Used to track who accessed the database, when, from where, and what they did.
Tools:
1.	Auditing:
â€¢	Logs access attempts, data reads/writes, and schema changes.
â€¢	Store in Log Analytics, Storage Account, or Event Hub.
â€¢	Supports filtering by action type, user, etc.
ðŸ’¡ Example: Who executed DELETE statements yesterday?
2.	Diagnostic Settings:
â€¢	Enable SQL security audit logs and connection/session metrics.
3.	Azure Monitor:
â€¢	View sessions, failed logins, and long-running queries.
4.	Query Store:
â€¢	Monitor query performance per user/session.
ðŸ“Œ Enables compliance, forensic analysis, and anomaly detection.
________________________________________
âœ… Security Best Practices Checklist
A high-level security checklist for Azure SQL and related resources:
ðŸ” Access Control
â€¢	âœ… Use Azure AD authentication
â€¢	âœ… Assign roles using AAD Groups, not individuals
â€¢	âœ… Apply RBAC at the resource group or server level
â€¢	âœ… Follow least privilege principles (no db_owner unless necessary)
ðŸ”’ Data Protection
