11. Manage Performance Using Alerts and Baselines
âœ… Create Metric Alerts (CPU, DTUs)
Metric alerts help you proactively monitor performance and trigger actions when resource usage crosses a defined threshold.
Common Metrics to Monitor:
â€¢	CPU usage (%)
â€¢	DTU usage (if on DTU-based tier)
â€¢	Storage size
â€¢	Deadlocks, failed connections, blocked sessions
How to Set Up:
You can configure alerts in the Azure Portal, Azure CLI, or PowerShell.
Steps (Portal):
1.	Go to your SQL Database or Server.
2.	Under Monitoring, choose Alerts.
3.	Click + New Alert Rule.
4.	Select a signal (e.g., "CPU Percent", "DTU Percentage").
5.	Define threshold (e.g., CPU > 80% for 5 min).
6.	Set an action group (email, SMS, webhook, or automation).
ðŸ’¡ Best Practice: Set alerts on both short-term spikes and long-term trends.
ðŸ“Œ Alerts help prevent downtime, detect anomalies, and guide scaling decisions.
________________________________________
âœ… Set Up Query Store Baselines
Query Store tracks query performance over time and helps detect regressions.
Key Features:
â€¢	Stores query plans, runtime stats, and execution history.
â€¢	Detects when a queryâ€™s performance degrades.
â€¢	Helps revert to a previous faster plan.
Setting a Baseline:
1.	Enable Query Store (if not already):
sql
CopyEdit
ALTER DATABASE [mydb]
SET QUERY_STORE = ON;
2.	Identify a stable, performant period and force a plan:
sql
CopyEdit
EXEC sp_query_store_force_plan @query_id = 123, @plan_id = 456;
3.	Optionally set Query Store Capture Policies:
o	Auto vs. custom
o	Capture only long-running or frequently executed queries
ðŸ’¡ Use baselines as reference points to compare new deployments or changes.
ðŸ“Œ Very useful in performance regression analysis and troubleshooting.
________________________________________
âœ… Thresholds for Auto-scaling and Throttling
Azure SQL offers scaling options based on usage, but they differ by pricing model.
________________________________________
ðŸš€ Auto-Scaling (vCore Model + Hyperscale or Serverless)
â€¢	Serverless Tier can automatically:
o	Pause during inactivity (saves cost)
o	Scale up/down vCores based on usage
â€¢	You can configure:
o	Minimum and maximum vCores
o	Auto-pause delay (in minutes)
ðŸ“Œ Ideal for sporadic workloads or development environments.
________________________________________
ðŸ’¡ Manual Scaling (DTU or vCore)
You can scale resources manually when metrics hit thresholds:
â€¢	If DTU % > 85% consistently, scale to higher tier.
â€¢	For vCore model, increase CPU/memory directly.
Use metric alerts to notify when thresholds are crossed:
â€¢	CPU > 80% for 15 minutes â†’ alert
â€¢	DTU > 90% average â†’ recommend scale-up
________________________________________
ðŸš« Throttling
When resource limits (CPU, DTU, IOPS) are exceeded:
â€¢	Requests are delayed or rejected
â€¢	Error codes like 10928 or 10929 appear
ðŸ“Œ Happens commonly in DTU-based models or under-provisioned vCore setups.
How to Mitigate:
â€¢	Monitor usage with alerts
â€¢	Use Elastic Pools for bursty workloads
â€¢	Scale up resources in advance or set serverless max vCores higher
________________________________________
ðŸ”„ Summary Table
Topic	Purpose	Key Tool
Metric Alerts	Monitor CPU, DTU, storage, etc.	Azure Monitor, Alerts
Query Store Baseline	Track and restore good plans	Query Store in SQL
Auto-scaling Thresholds	Optimize cost/performance	Serverless / Alerts
Throttling Detection	Prevent performance issues	Metrics + error codes
12. Monitor and Tune for Performance Bottlenecks
âœ… TempDB Contention
TempDB is a system database used for:
â€¢	Temporary tables and variables
â€¢	Sorting operations
â€¢	Hash joins and aggregates
â€¢	Version store for row versioning
In Azure SQL:
â€¢	You cannot configure TempDB directly (unlike on-prem)
â€¢	However, TempDB contention still occurs, especially with:
o	High concurrent workloads
o	Heavy use of temp tables or sorts
Symptoms:
â€¢	Slower query performance
â€¢	Wait types like PAGELATCH_UP or PAGELATCH_EX
Mitigation:
â€¢	Reduce reliance on temp tables
â€¢	Use table variables when appropriate
â€¢	Optimize queries with sorts, joins, or window functions
â€¢	Consider vCore models or Managed Instance, which provide more TempDB resources
ðŸ“Œ In SQL Managed Instance, you can configure multiple TempDB files (like in on-prem).
________________________________________
âœ… Resource Limits and Throttling
Azure SQL enforces resource governance to ensure fair use of shared infrastructure.
Common Resource Limits:
â€¢	DTU or vCore quota
â€¢	Storage IOPS and throughput
â€¢	Concurrent worker threads
â€¢	TempDB usage
Throttling Symptoms:
â€¢	Queries get delayed or fail
â€¢	Error codes like:
o	10928: Resource limit reached
o	10929: Too many concurrent requests
How to Handle Throttling:
â€¢	Monitor CPU, DTU, and IOPS using Azure Metrics
â€¢	Use Elastic Pools for bursty or multi-tenant workloads
â€¢	Scale up to a higher SKU or use Serverless tier with auto-scale
â€¢	Refactor heavy queries or batch them
ðŸ’¡ Long-running or poorly indexed queries can hit limits faster.
________________________________________
âœ… Performance Counters via Metrics
Azure exposes many SQL performance counters through Azure Monitor:
Useful Counters:
â€¢	CPU Percentage: Indicates compute pressure
â€¢	DTU Percentage: For DTU-based models
â€¢	Storage Used (%): Monitor disk space
â€¢	Deadlocks: Shows app/database concurrency issues
â€¢	Blocked by other sessions: Indicates locking contention
â€¢	IO Requests/Sec: IOPS usage, tied to disk limits
Access Metrics:
â€¢	Azure Portal â†’ SQL Database â†’ Monitoring â†’ Metrics
â€¢	Can export to Log Analytics or Grafana
ðŸ“Œ You can create alerts and dashboards based on these metrics.
________________________________________
âœ… Blocking, Deadlocks, Long-Running Queries
These are common causes of slow performance and user complaints.
ðŸ”’ Blocking:
Occurs when one query locks a resource and others are forced to wait.
â€¢	Often caused by:
o	Long transactions
o	Missing indexes
o	Poor query design
ðŸ“Œ Identify blocking chains via:
sql
CopyEdit
SELECT * FROM sys.dm_tran_locks
Or use Azure SQL Insights, Query Store, or Extended Events.
________________________________________
ðŸ’¥ Deadlocks:
Occurs when two or more queries hold locks that the other needs â€” results in one being killed.
â€¢	SQL Server picks a deadlock victim to resolve it.
â€¢	Monitor using:
o	Extended Events
o	SQL Audit logs
o	Log Analytics (Azure Monitor workspace)
ðŸ’¡ Use proper indexing, shorter transactions, and consistent access order to reduce deadlocks.
________________________________________
ðŸ•’ Long-Running Queries:
These consume resources and delay other users.
â€¢	Check in:
o	Query Performance Insight
o	Query Store (duration, CPU stats)
o	DMVs like sys.dm_exec_requests
Mitigation:
â€¢	Add indexes
â€¢	Break large operations into chunks
â€¢	Optimize query plans
________________________________________
ðŸ”„ Summary Table
Issue	Description	Tool/Detection
TempDB Contention	Bottleneck for temp objects	Wait stats, Managed Instance
Throttling	Resource limits cause delays	Azure Metrics, Error 10928/10929
Performance Counters	Live monitoring of usage	Azure Monitor, Metrics blade
Blocking	Locks hold up other queries	DMVs, Live Query Stats
Deadlocks	Circular locking, auto-kill	Extended Events, Logs
Long Queries	High resource use, slow apps	Query Store, Insights
